                  <summary>A short Christian prayer for divine assistance</summary>
                  <msItemStruct>
                     <note type="general">Side 1: 6 lines written with the fibers</note>
                     <note type="general">Side 2: a few words written in different directions, apparently to try a pen (Grenfell and Hunt)</note>
                     <note type="general">A large, rude uncial hand with generous space between letters</note>
                     <note type="general">Nomen sacrum th(eo)s in l. 1</note>
                     <note type="general">the phrase theos ton parakeimenon stauron, God of the crosses laid on, is unique, but presumably derived from Luke 9:23.</note>
                     <note type="local_note">Pap. 3, Special Collections, Luce Library, Princeton Theological Seminary, Princeton, N.J.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="grc">Greek</textLang>
                  </msItemStruct>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>9.2 x 11.9 cm. A single, mostly intact papyrus fragment; bottom right corner torn away; some wear top to bottom just right of center, perhaps suggesting a fold; adhesive stains on verso from a previous mounting.</support>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
